          <tr><td>Lost job revenue ($400 avg.)</td><td>$2,800</td><td>$84,000</td><td>$1,022,000</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The ad spend alone is painful — over $100K a year in clicks that went nowhere. But the lost revenue is where it really hurts. A single missed emergency call can mean a $600–$1,200 job that walks to a competitor who answered.</p>

      <h2>The Google Ads Feedback Loop Nobody Talks About</h2>
      <p>Google's ad algorithm optimizes for conversions. When your ad generates a call that goes to voicemail, Google doesn't know the lead was lost — it only knows the call didn't result in a tracked conversion. Over time, this creates a destructive feedback loop:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>More unanswered calls → fewer conversion signals → higher cost-per-click</li>
        <li>Higher CPC → same budget buys fewer clicks → fewer calls overall</li>
        <li>Fewer calls → fewer jobs → tighter budget → reduced ad spend</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Tradies who fix this loop by answering every call see their effective cost-per-lead drop by 40–60% within 60 days, simply because Google's algorithm starts seeing consistent conversion volume and rewards the account with lower CPCs. This is documented across our <a href="/blog/google-ads-for-plumbers/">Google Ads for plumbers guide</a> and related industry analysis.</p>

      <h2>Voicemail vs. Live Answering: The Conversion Gap</h2>
      <p>How much difference does actually answering make? Industry data from call-tracking platforms shows a stark gap:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Call answered live:</strong> 55–70% result in a booked appointment or scheduled estimate</li>
        <li><strong>Call goes to voicemail:</strong> Only 28% result in a callback (the 28% who do leave a message)</li>
        <li><strong>Call goes to voicemail + no message left:</strong> 0% — the lead is gone forever</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The difference between answering and not answering is the difference between a 60% close rate and a 28% close rate. No keyword optimization, landing page test, or bid adjustment can make up for that gap.</p>

      <h2>What 24/7 Call Recovery Looks Like for a Tradie</h2>
      <p>A proper call recovery system does not mean hiring a receptionist or using a basic answering service that takes messages. It means deploying an automated system that handles the entire call-to-appointment pipeline. Here is how the <a href="/sdr/">Missed Call Revenue Recovery System</a> handles an incoming lead:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Answers before the third ring</strong> — 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, including holidays</li>
        <li><strong>Verifies the caller</strong> — confirms they are a homeowner, asks for their postal code, and identifies the work type needed</li>
        <li><strong>Captures job details</strong> — scope, urgency, preferred time window, and any special instructions</li>
        <li><strong>Books the appointment</strong> — directly into your Google Calendar or preferred scheduling platform</li>
        <li><strong>Sends confirmation</strong> — both to you and the homeowner, with the appointment time and job details</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The system charges $1,300 setup and $25 per qualified appointment booked, or $997/month for unlimited appointments. That replaces the $100K+ in wasted ad spend from a single year of missed calls.</p>

